    "claim": "The contract accepts and stores an `exchangeRate` of zero, both during initialization and during normal oracle refreshes. `_isSolvent()` multiplies debt by `_exchangeRate`, so when the cached rate is zero the debt side of the solvency inequality becomes zero; any borrower with `borrowPart > 0` and at least 1 collateral share therefore passes solvency. `liquidate()` uses the same predicate, so those accounts are also skipped as supposedly solvent.",
    "impact": "If the oracle ever reports `(true, 0)` or the cache is otherwise set to zero, an attacker can post dust collateral, borrow most or all available MIM, and remove nearly all collateral while keeping a single share behind. The resulting position remains marked solvent and cannot be liquidated, leaving the market with bad debt and drained liquidity.",
    "paths": [
      "A zero-valued oracle response is cached through `updateExchangeRate()` or seeded at deployment.",
      "The attacker adds minimal collateral, borrows available MIM, removes collateral down to 1 share, and `liquidate()` keeps reverting with all targets considered solvent under the zero rate."
    ],
