    "claim": "`updateExchangeRate()` does not halt risk-sensitive actions when `oracle.get()` fails; it simply returns the previously cached `exchangeRate`. The `solvent` modifier used by `borrow()` and `removeCollateral()`, as well as the deferred check at the end of `cook()`, all accept that stale rate instead of requiring a fresh oracle result. `liquidate()` also uses the same stale cached rate after a failed update.",
    "impact": "During an oracle outage, positions continue to be judged against an outdated price. After a sharp market move, borrowers can over-borrow or withdraw too much collateral at a stale favorable valuation, while liquidations may lag the true market state and allow bad debt to accumulate.",
